        </div>
        <div class="receipt-row">
          <p class="receipt-item original-text" data-text-version="original" id="orig-paragraph-0040">Grass,</p>
          <p class="receipt-item transformed-text" data-text-version="transformed" id="trans-paragraph-0040">Lawn,</p>
          <p class="receipt-item original-text" data-text-version="original" id="orig-paragraph-0041">$1.00</p>
          <p class="receipt-item transformed-text" data-text-version="transformed" id="trans-paragraph-0041">$1.00</p>
        </div>
        <div class="receipt-row">
          <p class="receipt-item original-text" data-text-version="original" id="orig-paragraph-0042">Stalks,</p>
          <p class="receipt-item transformed-text" data-text-version="transformed" id="trans-paragraph-0042">Stems,</p>
          <p class="receipt-item original-text" data-text-version="original" id="orig-paragraph-0043">$0.75</p>
          <p class="receipt-item transformed-text" data-text-version="transformed" id="trans-paragraph-0043">75 cents</p>
        </div>
        <div class="receipt-row">
          <p class="receipt-item original-text" data-text-version="original" id="orig-paragraph-0044">In all,</p>
          <p class="receipt-item transformed-text" data-text-version="transformed" id="trans-paragraph-0044">Overall,</p>
          <p class="receipt-item original-text" data-text-version="original" id="orig-paragraph-0045">$23.44</p>
          <p class="receipt-item transformed-text" data-text-version="transformed" id="trans-paragraph-0045">$23.44</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="subsq original-text" data-text-version="original" id="orig-paragraph-0046">Leaving a pecuniary profit, as I have elsewhere said, of $8.71½.</p>
      <p class="subsq transformed-text hidden" data-text-version="transformed" id="trans-paragraph-0046">As I mentioned before, this resulted in a financial gain of $8.71.</p>
      <p class="subsq original-text" data-text-version="original" id="orig-paragraph-0047">This is the result of my experience in raising beans. Plant the common small white bush bean about the first of June, in rows three feet by eighteen inches apart, being careful to select fresh round and unmixed seed. First look out for worms, and supply vacancies by planting anew. Then look out for woodchucks, if it is an exposed place, for they will nibble off the earliest tender leaves almost clean as they go; and again, when the young tendrils make their appearance, they have notice of it, and will shear them off with both buds and young pods, sitting erect like a squirrel. But above all harvest as early as possible, if you would escape frosts and have a fair and salable crop; you may save much loss by this means.</p>
      <p class="subsq transformed-text hidden" data-text-version="transformed" id="trans-paragraph-0047">Here is what I've learned about growing beans. Plant the common small white bush bean around June 1st, in rows three feet apart and eighteen inches between plants. Be sure to choose fresh, round seeds that are all the same type. Watch out for worms at first, and replant any missing spots. Then keep an eye out for groundhogs, especially in open areas, as they will nibble the young leaves and later cut off the new shoots and pods while sitting up like a squirrel. Most importantly, harvest as soon as you can to avoid frost and ensure a good, marketable crop. Doing this can prevent a lot of loss.</p>
      <p class="subsq original-text" data-text-version="original" id="orig-paragraph-0048">This further experience also I gained. I said to myself, I will not plant beans and corn with so much industry another summer, but such seeds, if the seed is not lost, as sincerity, truth, simplicity, faith, innocence, and the like, and see if they will not grow in this soil, even with less toil and manurance, and sustain me, for surely it has not been exhausted for these crops. Alas! I said this to myself; but now another summer is gone, and another, and another, and I am obliged to say to you, Reader, that the seeds which I planted, if indeed they <i>were</i> the seeds of those virtues, were wormeaten or had lost their vitality, and so did not come up. Commonly men will only be brave as their fathers were brave, or timid. This generation is very sure to plant corn and beans each new year precisely as the Indians did centuries ago and taught the first settlers to do, as if there were a fate in it. I saw an old man the other day, to my astonishment, making the holes with a hoe for the seventieth time at least, and not for himself to lie down in! But why should not the New Englander try new adventures, and not lay so much stress on his grain, his potato and grass crop, and his orchards,—raise other crops than these? Why concern ourselves so much about our beans for seed, and not be concerned at all about a new generation of men? We should really be fed and cheered if when we met a man we were sure to see that some of the qualities which I have named, which we all prize more than those other productions, but which are for the most part broadcast and floating in the air, had taken root and grown in him. Here comes such a subtile and ineffable quality, for instance, as truth or justice, though the slightest amount or new variety of it, along the road. Our ambassadors should be instructed to send home such seeds as these, and Congress help to distribute them over all the land. We should never stand upon ceremony with sincerity. We should never cheat and insult and banish one another by our meanness, if there were present the kernel of worth and friendliness. We should not meet thus in haste. Most men I do not meet at all, for they seem not to have time; they are busy about their beans. We would not deal with a man thus plodding ever, leaning on a hoe or a spade as a staff between his work, not as a mushroom, but partially risen out of the earth, something more than erect, like swallows alighted and walking on the ground:—</p>
      <p class="subsq transformed-text hidden" data-text-version="transformed" id="trans-paragraph-0048">This additional experience I also gained. I told myself I wouldn't plant beans and corn with such hard work next summer, but instead seeds like honesty, truth, simplicity, faith, innocence, and the like. I wanted to see if they would grow in this soil, even with less effort and fertilizer, and sustain me, as surely the soil hasn't been depleted for these crops. Alas! I said this to myself, but now another summer has passed, and another, and I must tell you, Reader, that the seeds I planted, if they were indeed the seeds of those virtues, were worm-eaten or had lost their life force, and so did not sprout. Usually people will only be as brave or timid as their fathers were. This generation is certain to plant corn and beans each year just as the Indians did centuries ago and taught the first settlers, as if it's destined. I saw an old man the other day, to my surprise, making the holes with a hoe for at least the seventieth time, and not for himself to lie in! But why shouldn't the New Englander try new things and not focus so much on his grain, potato, grass, and orchard crops—why not raise other crops? Why do we care so much about our beans for seed, but not at all about a new generation of people? We would truly be nourished and uplifted if, when meeting someone, we were certain to see that some of the qualities I mentioned, which we value more than those other crops, but which are mostly scattered in the air, had taken root and grown in him. Here comes such a subtle and indescribable quality, like truth or justice, even in the smallest amount or new form, along the way. Our ambassadors should be told to send home such seeds, and Congress should help spread them across the land. We should never stand on ceremony with sincerity. We should never deceive, insult, and reject each other due to our pettiness, if the core of worth and kindness were present. We shouldn't meet so hastily. I don't encounter most men at all, as they seem to lack time; they are occupied with their beans. We wouldn't always deal with a man plodding along, leaning on a hoe or spade as a walking stick during his work, not like a mushroom, but partly risen from the earth, a bit more than upright, like swallows landed and walking on the ground.</p>
      <div class="alignment-block alignment-block-align-left inset-block">
        <div class="text-block">
          <p class="alignment-block-content alignment-block-content-left original-text" data-text-version="original" id="orig-paragraph-0049">“And as he spake, his wings would now and then </p>
          <p class="alignment-block-content alignment-block-content-left transformed-text hidden" data-text-version="transformed" id="trans-paragraph-0049">"As he spoke, his wings would occasionally</p>
          <p class="alignment-block-content alignment-block-content-left original-text" data-text-version="original" id="orig-paragraph-0050">Spread, as he meant to fly, then close again, </p>
          <p class="alignment-block-content alignment-block-content-left transformed-text hidden" data-text-version="transformed" id="trans-paragraph-0050">He spread his wings as if to fly, then closed them again,</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="subsq original-text" data-text-version="original" id="orig-paragraph-0051">so that we should suspect that we might be conversing with an angel. Bread may not always nourish us; but it always does us good, it even takes stiffness out of our joints, and makes us supple and buoyant, when we knew not what ailed us, to recognize any generosity in man or Nature, to share any unmixed and heroic joy. </p>
      <p class="subsq transformed-text hidden" data-text-version="transformed" id="trans-paragraph-0051">We may suspect we are talking to an angel. Bread doesn't always feed us, but it's always good for us. It loosens our stiff joints and makes us flexible and lively when we didn't know what was wrong. Recognizing any kindness in people or nature lets us feel pure and intense happiness.</p>
      <p class="subsq original-text" data-text-version="original" id="orig-paragraph-0052">Ancient poetry and mythology suggest, at least, that husbandry was once a sacred art; but it is pursued with irreverent haste and heedlessness by us, our object being to have large farms and large crops merely. We have no festival, nor procession, nor ceremony, not excepting our Cattle-shows and so called Thanksgivings, by which the farmer expresses a sense of the sacredness of his calling, or is reminded of its sacred origin. It is the premium and the feast which tempt him. He sacrifices not to Ceres and the Terrestrial Jove, but to the infernal Plutus rather. By avarice and selfishness, and a grovelling habit, from which none of us is free, of regarding the soil as property, or the means of acquiring property chiefly, the landscape is deformed, husbandry is degraded with us, and the farmer leads the meanest of lives. He knows Nature but as a robber. Cato says that the profits of agriculture are particularly pious or just, (<i>maximeque pius quæstus</i>), and according to Varro the old Romans “called the same earth Mother and Ceres, and thought that they who cultivated it led a pious and useful life, and that they alone were left of the race of King Saturn. </p>
      <p class="subsq transformed-text hidden" data-text-version="transformed" id="trans-paragraph-0052">Ancient poetry and mythology hint that farming was once a sacred art, but we pursue it with irreverent haste, focused only on having big farms and harvests. We have no festivals, processions, or ceremonies - not even our farm shows and Thanksgivings - where the farmer expresses the sacredness of his work or is reminded of its holy origins. He's tempted by rewards and feasts. He doesn't sacrifice to Ceres and the Earth God, but to the devilish Plutus instead. Greed, selfishness, and a base habit we all have of seeing land as mere property have deformed the countryside, degraded farming, and left the farmer living the lowliest life. He sees Nature only as something to exploit. Cato says farming profits are uniquely pious or just, and Varro notes the ancient Romans "called the earth Mother and Ceres, believing that those who tilled it led a pious and useful life, and that they alone remained of King Saturn's people."</p>
      <p class="subsq original-text" data-text-version="original" id="orig-paragraph-0053">We are wont to forget that the sun looks on our cultivated fields and on the prairies and forests without distinction. They all reflect and absorb his rays alike, and the former make but a small part of the glorious picture which he beholds in his daily course. In his view the earth is all equally cultivated like a garden. Therefore we should receive the benefit of his light and heat with a corresponding trust and magnanimity. What though I value the seed of these beans, and harvest that in the fall of the year? This broad field which I have looked at so long looks not to me as the principal cultivator, but away from me to influences more genial to it, which water and make it green. These beans have results which are not harvested by me. Do they not grow for woodchucks partly? The ear of wheat (in Latin <i>spica</i>, obsoletely <i>speca</i>, from <i>spe</i>, hope) should not be the only hope of the husbandman; its kernel or grain (<i>granum</i> from <i>gerendo</i>, bearing) is not all that it bears. How, then, can our harvest fail? Shall I not rejoice also at the abundance of the weeds whose seeds are the granary of the birds? It matters little comparatively whether the fields fill the farmer’s barns. The true husbandman will cease from anxiety, as the squirrels manifest no concern whether the woods will bear chestnuts this year or not, and finish his labor with every day, relinquishing all claim to the produce of his fields, and sacrificing in his mind not only his first but his last fruits also. </p>
      <p class="subsq transformed-text hidden" data-text-version="transformed" id="trans-paragraph-0053">We often forget that the sun shines on our farms, grasslands and woods equally. They all reflect and absorb its rays the same, and the farms are just a small part of the magnificent view it sees each day. From its perspective, the whole earth is evenly tended like a garden. So we should accept its light and warmth with matching faith and generosity. What does it matter that I prize the seeds of these beans and gather them in autumn? This vast field I've gazed at for so long doesn't see me as its main grower, but looks past me to more nurturing forces that irrigate and make it lush. These beans yield crops I don't harvest. Don't they grow partly for groundhogs too? The wheat stalk (in Latin spica, archaically speca, from spe, hope) shouldn't be the farmer's only aspiration; its seed or grain (granum from gerendo, bearing) isn't all that it carries. How then can our harvest ever disappoint? Shouldn't I also delight in the plentiful weeds whose seeds fill the birds' pantry? It matters little in the end if the fields stock the farmer's storehouses. The true farmer will let go of worry, just as squirrels show no distress over whether the forests will yield nuts this year, and complete his toil each day, giving up any right to the fruits of his lands, and relinquishing in his heart not just his early harvest but his late one too.</p>
